				<!--[Todo: markup citedRange elements if necessary]-->
				<p>The discovery of this “inscribed slab” was first reported in <bibl><ptr target="bib:ASI"/><citedRange>1934-35: 45-6</citedRange></bibl> and described as bilingual in Pyu and “an unknown language, probably Sanskrit”, claims repeated in <bibl><ptr target="bib:LeMay1956_01"/><citedRange>47</citedRange></bibl>. <bibl><ptr target="bib:Luce1985_01"/><citedRange>I, 65, 75 n. 25, 131</citedRange></bibl>, provides an overview and describes the inscription as “8 lines of Tircul [Pyu] and 8 interlinear lines of Brahmi”. <bibl><ptr target="bib:SeinWin2016_01"/><citedRange>84-7</citedRange></bibl> provides a new reading in Burmese script. Re-edited here from our team’s RTIs.</p>
